column10: Multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular and ductal carcinoma, left breast
column11: Participant’s mammogram on 07/12/2017 showed a small 6 MM speculated density in the upper outer quadrant of the left breast. She had a left lateral biopsy on her breast on 07/20/2017 and was diagnosed with recurrent invasive carcinoma, ER/PR positive and HER-2 negative by FISH. She was treated surgically with left breast wide local excision on 08/01/2017. Pathology showed multifocal infiltrating mixed lobular (85%) and ductal (15%) carcinoma, Nottingham Grade 3 (score 2 for tubule formation, 3 for nuclear atypia, and 3 for mitosis). DCIS is present. No necrosis of the invasive carcinoma was identified and it measured 2.6 X 2.6 X 3.0 CM. The participant had a left breast re-excision on 08/22/2017 which showed two foci of residual invasive mixed mammary carcinoma (largest focus measuring 12 MM) with 1 MM focal positive margin. Her oncologist prescribed her Anastrozole 1mg QD PO. More oncology records have been requested.

column43: DMS 6/24/19 - Subject with PMH of GERD , HTN, hyperlipodemia presented to local ER with complaints of acute nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain. Pain began 2300 on 4/12/19. Initially attributed to "food poisoning"  but when pain persisted presented to ER. CT abdominal scan showed partial small bowel obstruction.  On exam epigastic and RUQ tenderness present. General surgery was contacted to place a nasogasrtric (NG) tube.  Prior to ER, at home had several episodes of nonbloody no bilious emesis. Had normal bowel movement about one hour after pain began. Was admitted for continued NG tube decompression and IV fluids.  By4/14/19 subject was passing flatus, denied nausea, emesis. NG tube with 1375 ml gastric content. Labs revealed no leukocytosis . H & H stable, electrolytes WNL. No evidence of acute kidney injury. NGT removed and started on clear liquids. Recieved pantoprazole IV for GERD while admitted and had prn zofran IV ordered. By 4/15/19 subject continued to improve. Felt well after breakfast. Labs and vitals were normal subject was discharged home.

column43:
IM 3/19/19
This is an 88 year old male who presents on 2/13/19 with nausea and abdominal pain. Patient was found to have initially symptomatic cholelithiasis and HIDA scan positive for acute cholecystitis. He was placed on IV antibiotics and followed up for hyponatremia. On February 14, 2019, patient underwent elective laparoscopic cholecystectomy with intraoperative cholangiogram showing no retained stones. Due to liver masses, he also underwent wedge biopsy X2. He was placed back on diet and monitored on pain control and for bowel function. Continued to improve through hospitalization, tolerating well. On day of discharge (2/16/19), was passing flatus, tolerating full diet, on po pain control and was cleared by specialists.
Laboratory data: BMP shows sodium 134 from 124, potassium 4.3, chloride 103, bicarb 22, NUN 18, creatinine 0.78, glucose 101, calcium 7.9. Cholesterol 172, HDL 33, LDL 124, triglycerides 77.
Imaging studies: HIDA scan shows acute cholecystitis, photopenic areas of right liver inferiorly and left liver superiorly. Hepatic parenchyma shows persistent activity over time, suggesting intrahepatic cholestasis or hepatocellular dysfunction. 
Final diagnosis: 1. Acute cholecystitis, 2. Hyponatremia 3. Hypertension 4. Dementia, 5. Leukocytosis, 6. Liver mass
Medications: Percocet 5/225 one po q.6 hours prn pain 2. Augmentin 875mg bid x5days 3. Vitamin C daily 4. Biotin daily 5. Buproprion XL 150mg daily 7. melatonin at bedtime 8. Multivitamin daily 9. CoQ10 daily 10. Buspirone 15mg bid 11. Aricept 20mg at bedtime

IM 2/19/19
Awaiting medical records from the hospital.

After sleeping in, both caregiver, daughter, and participant went straight in to take shower together around 12:30 PM. After several minutes, in hot shower, participant complained of dizziness and fainted. Daughter caught her and lowered her down. Eyes were open, breathing normally, but unresponsive for about two minutes. Afterward, participant got up and was back to her baseline. Resumed usual activities and behavior for remainder of day. And since then, no recurrences. Given that participant was "back to normal" so quickly. Family did not seek medical attention. At the time: no slurred speech, no facial droop, no extremity weakness, numbness, or tingling. No chest pain or palpitations. No dyspnea. No recent illness. No fever or chills. No seizures. 
OF NOTE: Participant's usual routine is to get up between 6AM and 8AM and eat breakfast around 8 AM. On the day of the event, participant was drowsy and had not eaten or drank anything prior to taking a hot shower. This suggests vasovagal syncope.

Subject had minor stroke on 9/3/2020 overnight. She went to the grocery store and found she could not make a left turn in traffic. On getting home, she could not follow the storylines of TV show and book she was reading. 3 days later, she had difficulty sleeping and not eating well. She saw her primary care doctor, tests were negative. On Friday 11th, she had headache and abdominal blockage and was taken to the hospital when MRI and Ultrasound of carotid artery were repeated. She stayed two nights (11th and 12th). results were negative but the neurologist on further review found one very small spot that looks like it, but will do more workup. She stopped walking on Tuesday 14th, started physical therapy on 14th. By Thursday 16th, she started walking a little bit. She is still confused, sleeps 4 hours and will be following up with neurologist for more workup.

IM 10/20/2020
Obtained medical records show admission diagnosis to be altered mental status. Subject was taken off memantine in February 2020 by her neurologist because she was doing well. After that they noticed she had significant changes to her memory and was having increasing difficulty. Due to COVID they could not see the neurologist, but they later saw him 2 weeks prior to admission on 9/11/2020 and asked him to put her back on Namenda (Memantine). She restarted Namenda and has had declining mentation. On Friday 9/4/2020, she was trying to drive around, she could not figure out the direction to go and then she discontinued driving. Over the weekend, she got more confused, she went to her primary care physician who ordered CT scan, blood and urine tests. CT scan of head and blood/urine tests were unremarkable but subject continued to remain confused. She was brought to the ER and admitted on 9/11/2020. MRI done on 9/12/2020 show no intracranial abnormality, no evidence of acute infarction and 4 mm dural based left inferior posterior falx possibly meningioma. Follow up MRI recommended in 6 months. Subject also complained she has been sleeping poorly. She described sleeping for 2 to 3 hours then suddenly awakening and unable to return to sleep. She also complained of stomach pains and constipation. She was discharged on 9/13/2020 at 16:41 and told to discontinue Namenda. Altered mental status was attributed to acute memantine side effects. She did not have stroke symptoms, no infection. Ammonia negative, TSH and T4 negative.

GI bleed with associated coffee ground emesis, leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactic acidosis, myoglobinemia, diarrhea, resulting in patient's death.
column43: Patient began having coffee ground emesis during the evening of 6 June 2020.  Nursing home sent patient to emergency room and she was admitted to the hospital on 7 June 2020.  She was initially noted to be hypotensive with blood pressure of 70/37.  Lab work showed multiple derangements including leukocytosis, acute kidney injury, lactate 5.4 mmol/L, and myoglobin > 24,000.  She had non-bloody foul-smelling diarrhea.  She was given IV bolus fluids and had improvement in blood pressure.  Diagnosis was GI bleed due to suspected significant intra-abdominal pathology with main concern for ischemic bowel.  Lengthy discussion was had with patient's son/healthcare proxy who is at the bedside.  Due to patient's and sons wishes, decision was made to forego aggressive workup or management.  She was transitioned to comfort care measures including around the clock and as needed analgesia with Dilaudid, Ativan for restlessness, and Haldol for agitation.  Patient expired at 4:40 on 8 jun 2020.  Son called site at 8:38 on 8 Jun 2020 to report.

AE #2 Stage 1 Pancreatic Cancer:
1/24/2020 presented after 2½ days of painless jaundice, change in stool & urine color, itching, and decreased appetite.  Additionally, he reported intentional weight loss of 10-12 pounds since mid-December 2019.  Further evaluation indicated elevated bilirubin and elevated liver function tests.  MRCP was obtained which showed an approximately 2.5 cm mass in the head of the pancreas.  This was followed up with an endoscopic ultrasound, ERCP, and stent placement; at that time a biopsy was obtained which was consistent with adenocarcinoma.  An exploratory laparotomy was completed 2/19/2020 and was negative for any metastasis
Discontinued Claritin on 2/6/2020
Chemotherapy 2/24/2020 commenced with Folfirinox 5FU                   
(Admitted to hospital for SAE # 2)
3/17/2020 Chemotherapy continued – new drug Gemcitabine  Doses on 3/24, 4/14, 4/28, 5/12, 5/26, 6/24, 7/1, 7/15
6/24/2020-7/15/2020 Radiation: Pancreas: IMRT: 45 Gy in 15 fractions
8/19/2020 Surgical procedure: tumor resection
8/19/2020-9/16/2020 Hospitalization: Status post laparoscopic converted to open standard Whipple with reconstruction of the portal vein utilizing synthetic material and subsequent repair of umbilical hernia on 8/19/2020.  Post op course included:
•	Intra-op bile cultures returned positive for multi-drug resistant gram-negative bacilli – managed with cefepime, ciprofloxacin, and vancomycin.
•	Superficial site infection - drainage from abdominal midline incision – sutures placed; amoxicillin and cefadroxil 
•	Occlusion of the SMV graft – started high intensity heparin drip that was transitioned to Lovenox
•	Acute kidney injury – managed medically with Lasix and avoidance of further nephrotoxic medications.
•	Atrial Fibrillation with rapid ventricular response – started diltiazem
•	Thrombocytopenia; multifactorial – transfused platelets intermittently
•	Anemia – transfused red blood cells intermittently
•	Hypokalemia
•	 Ileus
•	Diarrhea – pancreatic enzyme insufficiency CREON
•	Ascites
•	Total parental nutrition

11/25/2020  Presented to the ER with weakness, altered mental status, and shortness of breath.  He was found to be slightly hypoxic and tachypneic requiring 2L supplemental oxygen.  Work-up ensued and given his recent positive COVID-19 test, he was started on a 5-day course of remdesivir.  Additionally, a course of Dexamethasone was started, ending 4 days later due to resolution of oxygen requirements.  Insulin was administered during the hospital stay for steroid-induced hyperglycemia.  He was evaluated for homegoing oxygen and found not to require any.  He was discharged home on room air, without steroids, and without additional insulin.
